Why ingress, services do not go far enough.

You already have services. They handle layer four routing inside the cluster, and with the load balancer type, they can expose a workload publicly. So why is the service not the whole answer.

Because one load balancer per service is expensive and rigid. In a cloud cluster, each load balancer service provisions a separate cloud load balancer. That means real money, tens of dollars a month, for each one. A separate public address per load balancer, which is hard to brand. No h-t-t-p level routing, so you cannot say, send slash ay-pee-eye to the ay-pee-eye service and slash static to the static service. No tee-el-ess termination at the load balancer, so each pod has to do tee-el-ess itself. And no host based routing, so you cannot share one address between two host names.

What you actually want is one public entry point in front of many services, with h-t-t-p aware routing. That is what an ingress gives you. A single load balancer, one public address, fans out to many in cluster services, based on the h-t-t-p host name and the request path.

So one address can route, say, the ay-pee-eye host to the ay-pee-eye service, the main site's slash ay-pee-eye path to the ay-pee-eye service, everything else on the main site to the web service, and the shop host to the shop service. And it terminates tee-el-ess for all of them in one place. To put it simply, a service exposes one workload at layer four, while an ingress is a smart, shared, h-t-t-p front door for the whole cluster.
